\begin{abstract}
This study applies frequency-domain signal processing techniques to electrodermal activity (EDA) and heart rate variability, represented through RR interval data, collected during baseline (rest) and postural (yoga) states from 16 subjects ($n = 14{,}716$ samples). The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) was applied to both signals after removal of the DC component to isolate meaningful frequency content. An independent two-sample $t$-test (Welch's $t$-test) was conducted on FFT magnitude values within the 0--0.1~Hz range to statistically evaluate differences between the two states. Results indicate that both EDA ($t=-2.5127$, $p = 0.0122$) and RR interval ($t=-5.5743$, $p < 0.000001$) signals show statistically significant increases in frequency-domain amplitude during the postural state relative to baseline, suggesting heightened sympathetic nervous system activity during yoga postures. These findings demonstrate that signal processing alone, without machine learning classification, is sufficient to differentiate physiological states.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
electrodermal activity, heart rate variability, Fast Fourier Transform, signal processing, t-test, yoga, sympathetic nervous system
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

Wearable physiological sensors enable continuous, non-invasive monitoring of the autonomic nervous system (ANS) through signals such as electrodermal activity (EDA) and heart rate, derived here through RR interval (the time between successive heartbeats). Changes in ANS balance between sympathetic (``fight-or-flight'') and parasympathetic (``rest-and-digest'') activity are reflected in measurable changes to these signals. Physical activities such as yoga postures are known to influence ANS activity differently from a resting baseline state.

Prior work using wearable datasets has typically relied on machine learning (ML) classifiers trained on extracted features to differentiate physiological states. While effective for classification tasks, this approach does not directly establish whether the underlying signals are statistically distinguishable on their own. This study instead investigates whether frequency-domain signal processing techniques --- independent of any ML model --- can reveal and statistically confirm physiological differences between a resting baseline state and an active postural (yoga) state.

Specifically, we apply the FFT to EDA and RR interval signals collected during baseline and postural states, remove the DC (zero-frequency) component to isolate meaningful signal variation, and apply an independent $t$-test to the resulting frequency-domain amplitudes to assess statistical significance.

\section{Related Work}

Schmidt \textit{et al.} introduced a wearable device dataset collected via the Empatica E4 sensor capturing EDA, blood volume pulse (BVP), heart rate, skin temperature, and accelerometry during induced stress and structured exercise sessions, intended to support classification of activity states for applications such as closed-loop insulin delivery systems \cite{schmidt2025}. This dataset establishes EDA and heart-rate-derived signals as primary modalities for distinguishing sympathetic activation states.

Separately, pilot studies on commercial activity monitors (e.g., Fitbit) have shown that wearable feedback can sustain physical activity behavior over time, supporting the practical viability of wearable-based monitoring, though evidence on long-term efficacy remains mixed \cite{jhse}.

Work examining skin temperature as an indicator of cognitive flow state demonstrated that single-signal analysis is often insufficient to reliably characterize physiological state, motivating multimodal approaches that combine signals such as EDA, BVP, temperature, and accelerometry \cite{flowtemp}.

Prior wearable-based yoga research has applied machine learning to distinguish baseline, sympathetic, and parasympathetic states using ACC, BVP, EDA, and temperature signals \cite{anumula2023}. That work, however, relied on a trained classifier rather than direct statistical comparison of frequency-domain signal properties, which is the gap this study addresses.

\section{Methods}

\subsection{Participants and Data Acquisition}
Data were collected from 16 participants (subjects 1--16) using a wrist-worn wearable sensor recording multiple physiological signals during Iyengar yoga practice. The dataset comprised $14{,}716$ samples, including RR interval (ms), EDA ($\mu$S), BVP, accelerometry, gyroscopy, and temperature. Two experimental conditions were recorded: resting baseline ($n = 2{,}235$ samples) and postural yoga activity ($n = 12{,}481$ samples).

\subsection{Signal Preprocessing --- DC Removal}
Prior to spectral analysis, DC removal was performed independently on each state's signal segment by subtracting the segment mean:
\begin{equation}
  x_0(n) = x(n) - \mu_x
  \label{eq:dc}
\end{equation}
where $x(n)$ is the original signal and $\mu_x$ is its mean. This eliminates the zero-frequency component that would otherwise dominate the FFT spectrum and obscure physiologically relevant frequency-band differences.

\subsection{Fast Fourier Transform}
The one-sided FFT magnitude spectrum was computed for each condition using SciPy's FFT implementation:
\begin{equation}
  |X(k)| = \left| \text{FFT}\{x_0(n)\} \right|, \quad k = 0, 1, \ldots, \frac{N}{2}
  \label{eq:fft}
\end{equation}
Only frequencies in the 0--0.1~Hz range were retained for subsequent statistical comparison, excluding high-frequency components dominated by measurement noise.

\subsection{Statistical Analysis}
Welch's independent-samples $t$-test (\texttt{scipy.stats.ttest\_ind}, \texttt{equal\_var=False}) was used to compare FFT magnitude distributions between baseline and postural conditions for both EDA and RR interval signals, with a significance threshold of $\alpha = 0.05$.

