\caption{Welch's Independent T-Test Results on DC-Removed FFT Magnitudes (0--0.1 Hz)}
\label{tab:ttest}
\begin{tabular}{llrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Signal} & \textbf{Group} & \textbf{Mean Amp.} & \textbf{Result} \\
\midrule
EDA & Baseline & 92.28 & $t = -2.5127$ \\
($\mu$S)    & Postural & 145.14 & $p = 0.0122^{*}$ \\
\midrule
RR Interval & Baseline & 10{,}444.47 & $t = -5.5743$ \\
(ms)        & Postural & 16{,}966.50 & $p < 0.000001^{*}$ \\
\bottomrule
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\footnotesize{* Statistically significant at $\alpha = 0.05$.}}
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

For EDA, the postural state exhibited a mean FFT magnitude approximately 1.57 times higher than baseline (145.14 vs.\ 92.28), a difference that was statistically significant ($t = -2.5127$, $p = 0.0122$). For RR interval, the postural state exhibited a mean FFT magnitude approximately 1.62 times higher than baseline (16,966.50 vs.\ 10,444.47), with a substantially stronger level of significance ($t = -5.5743$, $p < 0.000001$).

\section{Discussion}

Both EDA and RR interval signals showed statistically significant increases in low-frequency (0--0.1~Hz) FFT magnitude during the postural yoga state relative to baseline rest. This is consistent with established autonomic physiology: increased skin conductance (EDA) reflects heightened sympathetic arousal \cite{boucsein2012electrodermal}, while increased low-frequency power in RR interval suggests greater autonomic modulation of heart rate during postural activity \cite{thayer2007role}.

Notably, the RR interval signal exhibited a substantially smaller $p$-value than EDA, indicating a stronger and more consistent separation between states in the heart-rate-variability domain. This suggests RR interval may be a more robust single-signal discriminator of baseline versus postural states than EDA alone, although both signals independently support the same conclusion.

These results demonstrate that meaningful, statistically validated differentiation between physiological states can be achieved through frequency-domain signal processing and classical hypothesis testing alone, without training a machine learning classifier.

A key limitation is the sample imbalance (2,235 baseline vs.\ 12,481 postural samples), which may influence statistical power. Additionally, the FFT was computed on the full state-concatenated signal rather than per-subject. Future work should apply per-subject FFT analysis to confirm consistency across individuals and explore band-specific spectral features (VLF, LF, HF) rather than aggregate FFT magnitude alone.

\section{Conclusion}

This paper demonstrated that postural yoga activity induces statistically significant changes in the frequency-domain representation of both EDA and RR interval signals recorded from 16 participants. After DC removal, Welch's independent $t$-tests confirmed significant FFT magnitude differences for EDA ($t = -2.5127$, $p = 0.0122$) and RR interval ($t = -5.5743$, $p < 0.000001$). These findings support frequency-domain signal processing as a viable, standalone approach for distinguishing autonomic states from wearable sensor data, without requiring a trained machine learning model.

